'''The list of countries obtaining independence from Spain''' is a list of countries that broke away from [[Spain]] for independence, or occasionally incorporation into another country, as depicted in the map below. These processes came about at different periods and world regions starting in the 17th century (Portugal).
==Independence waves== Since its beginnings in the 16th century, the [[Spanish Empire|Spanish empire]] conquered new areas starting out from its Castilian core kingdom. In 1597, the Spanish (Castilian) crown lost the [[Netherlands|Netherlands (Holland)]]. In 1640, Portugal split away after [[Philip II of Spain|Philip II]] had incorporated it to its domains in 1581. A second independence tide came about following the [[American Revolutionary War|Independence of the Thirteen Colonies]] in North America and the [[Battle of Trafalgar]] that heralded the end of the Spanish Atlantic hegemony. [[History of Venezuela|Venezuela]] (1811), under the influence of [[Guipuzcoan Company of Caracas|the Basque Enlightenment]], [[Spanish American wars of independence|sparked the independence movements of Central and Southern America]], spearheaded by [[Simón Bolívar|Simon Bolivar]].<ref name="ThoughtCo">{{cite web|title=Humanities › History & Culture Independence from Spain in Latin America|url=https://www.thoughtco.com/independence-from-spain-in-latin-america-2136406|website=ThoughtCo|publisher=Dotdash|accessdate=25 November 2017}}</ref><ref name="latinamericanstudies">{{cite web|title=Simón Bolívar: The Liberator|url=http://www.latinamericanstudies.org/liberators/bolivar.htm|website=latinamericanstudies.org|publisher=Dr. Antonio Rafael de la Cova|accessdate=25 November 2017}}</ref>
[[Restoration (Spain)|During the Spanish Restoration]] in the late 19th century, the last major colonies Cuba, Puerto Rico and Philippines detached from the metropolis with the support of the United States. Since the 50s of the 20th century, Spain lost the last continental lands in Africa, [[Spanish protectorate in Morocco]], [[Ifni]], [[Equatorial Guinea]] and [[Western Sahara]].<ref name="latinamericanstudies"/><ref name="ThoughtCo"/> [[File:List of Countries that have gained independece from Spain Euskara.svg|thumb|center|800px|Map of former Spanish colonies and possessions (with labels in Basque).]]
